#AnimalReview - â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸â­ï¸  #Animal is a FAMILY DRAMA ON STEROIDS.. Story of a greatest son who goes to unimaginable extent to protect his father.   Sandeep Reddy Vanga narrated a saga which has Substance, violence, emotions & powerful drama. Film is 3.20 hrs long but doesnâ€™t feel like one due immensely engaging screenplay that has high points and elevation moments throughout the run time.   #RanbirKapoor gives new definition to Alpha Male Characters. He outperformed himself in both intense & action scenes. Multiple shades his character posses is crazy & he performed them BRILLIANTLY with tremendous intensity . Vanga has given him once in a lifetime role which would be cherished by his audience for years to come.   #BobbyDeol cameo will leave you Spellbound,one the most insanely written role & he nailed it with FINESSE.   #AnilKapoor & #RashmikaMandanna acts are TOP NOTCH.  FANTASTIC Interval Block, Superb BGM, confrontational scenes of Ranbir -Anil kapoor & last 30 mins are the major highlights.   Dont miss the Post Credit scene, it will blow your mind away.   Overall #Animal is the most unconventional action & family drama you will witness..   #SandeepReddyVanga paints the celluloid with NEVER SEEN BEFORE BlOOD, VIOLENCE AND VENGEANCE.   BLOCKBUSTER

To add to the #Animal conversation, as an audience, we should come out of the whole Hero-Villain-Black and white mentality. This is the reason why our scripts are so monotonous and predictable and our actors repeat the same roles over and over. In the cases where there's even a hint of grey like in the case of Temper, Ravanasura or others, it's revealed in the end that in some round about way, the "Hero" is doing it for the greater good. This convenient plot device is bad writing in my opinion.  Indian audience and in particular Telugu audience are big hypocrites in my opinion. They're willing to accept Anti heroes, dark characters, and overall non message oriented stories when it's an English movie or even Malayalam movie, but when a Telugu director does it, they cry foul and talk about the messaging and bad influence the movie has on people.   This is the reason there are no original Telugu movies.   This is the reason the great Mahesh Babu is still stuck sending messages into the void like E.T..   Repeat after me  1.Lead characters being dark/grey in nature is also fun and interesting. 2. Movies don't have to carry a message to society. They can also be a story that's being told.  3. Gatekeeping destroys creativity.   #AnimalTheFilm

The actor in him is fully utilised by #SandeepReddyVanga who has once again managed to hit the bullâ€™s eye. Packaged with emotions, drama & action. #AnimalReview   Animalâ€™s first half is the driving force which is absolutely brilliant & flawless. The build up, transformation & the dialogues, all are lit. To sum it up, if the entire film had just the first half, it wouldâ€™ve been a 4.5/5.   #AnilKapoor does a terrific job, his skillset can never be questioned. #Rashmika & others do well. When it comes to performances, all of them are solid.  #BobbyDeol had limited screen-time (that too the 2nd half) but even those moments delivered. The actor who played his translator also deserves a special mention for his commendable performance.  The writing of the film is very good & Sandeep Vanga literally knows how to extract the best work from his actors. In fact his patented craft is visible when Ranbir in a few scenes will remind you of Shahid Kapoor from Kabir Singh.   Ranbirâ€™s body language, look, dialogue  delivery & screen presence will compel you to refer to him as SSRK.   On the whole, Animal is a must watch. Animal, Gandhi & Violence:  Once again, @imvangasandeep's #Animal sparks a debate on violence. Thanks to Sandeep for triggering conversations on this taboo subject. Conversations are always healthy for the society.   Violence and sex are the most hypocritically explained themes in our society.  While human instinct has a violent side in our DNA, we are also capable of non-violence. Non-violence, however, struggles to compete with the profit-driven violence business.  A quick glimpse at the History of the World reveals a stark reality â€“ violence has been a constant, with wars raging 90% of the time globally. Gandhiâ€™s concept of non-violence, though good philosophically, failed in practice. Surrendering to violence is itself an act of violence.  Gandhiâ€™s skewed justification of non-violence provides a cover for hypocrites. If cinema mirrors society, our hypocritical love for violence is evident.  Violence transcends groups, parties, and ideologies. It permeates politics, religions, regions, and communities. Urban Naxalism, divisive social media posts, and everyday interactions reflect this dangerous trend.  Did you speak against the Kashmir genocide? Social media runs on algorithms promoting hate and violence. Have you quit in protest?  I've seen your violence against me, my family, and my work. You stood silent against the violence triggered on me. Your violence is veiled as social justice.  I am not going to use inane arguments like 'don't like it, don't watch' or 'make your own counter-narrative,' etc. Such childish arguments are reserved for SJW wokes. The film is out, and everyone has a right to opine. But your opinion has to be based on a reality check. Not outside. Inside your own heart and mind.   You hate Reddy because it exposes your sophisticated violence, more dangerous than raw aggression. Violence is inherent in the universe.   Art is never toxic. Art provokes toxic people to make them aware of their toxicity.   Btw, it has been observed that showing raw violence makes people think more about non-violence.   Disclaimer: I haven't seen the film.

*Some thoughts on #Animal*  Why I have not watched it.   Why I still await a Vanga film.  #Starts  I have not watched Animal. I am tempted to make a pseudo analysis without watching. The thing with me is that if I don't want to watch a film, I won't. Because I know what's in it. Did not watch The Kashmir Files because you know what the film is. Likewise, I did not watch Animal. Although I was looking foward to watch it even after seeing glimpses of what they are calling 'Vangaism' in the film's teaser and trailer.  And I watch all kinds of films. You won't believe it. I watched Tadap which stars Suniel Shetty's son Ahan, whose acting skills is same as mine as a chemical science expert. I have watched the Vicky Kaushal and Sara Ali Khan's boring drama-comedy whose name I have forgotten and don't care googling. I watched Salman Khan's Antim too. I watched Cirkus which did not make me laugh. All of them in theatres. I also watched Raksha Bandhan. Ya, I did.   I gave all these films a chance to woo me. They all failed. But I cannot give Animal a chance. Especially now, after reading some reviews.  I watched Arjun Reddy for 30 minutes back in 2018 when Kabir Singh had not been devised yet. The trailer had me gripped. But for the first 30 minutes, I could not find any meaning in the film. I could not find the direction in which it was going. It all seemed meaningless. The valid criticism of the film that it is misognyst, objectifies women in some scenes did not even cross my mind. I was more bored than angered. And that's my biggest disappointment with Vanga.  Kabir Singh came and I tried watching. This time the critics' 'misogynist' label on the film had more effect on me. But my problem as a cinema watcher remained the same: I just could not watch it because there was nothing in the film to watch for.   And it is nothing to do with Kabir Singhs and Animals not being my flavour. I have watched many films that are not of my flavour.   That brings me to my problem with Sandeep Reddy Vanga. I have no problem with his violence. Yes, his alpha male characters are a big problem. But I am still ready to give these characters a chance. However, there is one big problem occurs when Vanga writes them. He writes them with an intention to prove an unnecessary point as a dominant male. His male characters are a problem because they have no purpose. Eventually, the films lose depth. What you watch then is a long drag. Vanga can achieve something more with the world he creates, but he chooses to go the other way.   There is no reason why he does that. But he does that. It could be to do with his good understanding of the market and the pulse of the nation. Or it could be a great risk paying off. A great co-incident of his idea of a man in the soceity being accepted so widely. And now, there is no going back on this as all of these characters have worked.   Vanga packages his male characters in such a way that it is hard for the growing up boys not to get influenced. Long hair, thick beard, dark shades, on the bike, in the car, with a gun in the hand, walking with the swagger with loud music being played in the background. The alpha male is ready. His male leads carry a sense of machoism that many men in the country strive for.   Vanga understands art. There is a great sense of aesthetic in his films which is what drew me initially to Animal after the trailer. But, to me, there has to be more than that. Lack of morality and empathy cannot provide depth to the films. He has every right to make his next. I am willing to watch it. I see a great filmmaker in Vanga. I just wish he has better stories to tell. But now even if he wants to change, the market won't let him.  #Ends #SandeepReddyVanga #RanbirKapoor
